<REFENTRY id="hostname">
<REFMETA><REFENTRYTITLE>hostname</REFENTRYTITLE></REFMETA>

<REFNAMEDIV>
<REFNAME>hostname</REFNAME>

<REFPURPOSE>
show or set the system's host name
</REFPURPOSE>

</REFNAMEDIV>

<REFSYNOPSISDIV>
<CMDSYNOPSIS>
<COMMAND>hostname</COMMAND>
<ARG>-v</ARG>
<GROUP><ARG>-a</ARG><ARG>--alias</ARG></GROUP>
<GROUP><ARG>-d</ARG><ARG>--domain</ARG></GROUP>
<GROUP><ARG>-f</ARG><ARG>--fqdn</ARG><ARG>--long</ARG></GROUP>
<GROUP><ARG>-i</ARG><ARG>--ip-address</ARG></GROUP>
<GROUP><ARG>-s</ARG><ARG>--short</ARG></GROUP>
<GROUP><ARG>-y</ARG><ARG>--yp</ARG><ARG>--nis</ARG></GROUP>
<SBR>
<COMMAND>hostname</COMMAND>
<ARG>-v</ARG>
<GROUP><ARG>-F <replaceable>file</replaceable></ARG><ARG>--file <replaceable>file</replaceable></ARG></GROUP>
<GROUP><ARG>-y</ARG><ARG>--yp</ARG><ARG>--nis</ARG></GROUP>
<ARG>name</ARG>
<SBR>
<COMMAND>hostname</COMMAND>
<ARG>-v</ARG>
<GROUP><ARG>-h</ARG><ARG>--help</ARG></GROUP>
<GROUP><ARG>-V</ARG><ARG>--version</ARG></GROUP>
</CMDSYNOPSIS>
</REFSYNOPSISDIV>


<REFSECT1>
<TITLE>Description</TITLE>
<PARA>
<COMMAND>hostname</COMMAND> is used to either display or, with appropriate
privileges, set the current host or domain
name of the system.  The host name is used by many applications
to identify the machine. The NIS domain name is also used by
NIS.
</PARA>

<PARA>
When called without any arguments, the program displays the name of
the system as returned by the <FUNCTION>gethostname</FUNCTION> function.
</PARA>

<PARA>
When called with a <PARAMETER>name</PARAMETER> argument or with the 
<PARAMETER>--file</PARAMETER> option, and the user has appropriate
privilege, the command
sets the host name. If any of the <PARAMETER>-y</PARAMETER>,
<PARAMETER>--yp</PARAMETER>, or <PARAMETER>--nis</PARAMETER> options are specified,
the NIS domain name is set instead.
</PARA>

</REFSECT1>

<REFSECT1>
<title>Options</title>
<variablelist>

<varlistentry>
<term>-a, --alias</term>
<listitem>
<para>
displays the alias name of the host (if used).
</para>
</listitem>
</varlistentry>

<varlistentry>
<term>-d, --domain</term>
<listitem>
<para>
displays the name of the DNS domain. 
</para>
</listitem>
</varlistentry>

<varlistentry>
<term>-F, --file filename</term>
<listitem>
<para>
reads the host name from the specified file. Comments (lines starting
with a `#') are ignored.
</para>
</listitem>
</varlistentry>

<varlistentry>
<term>-f, --fqdn, --long</term>
<listitem>
<para>
displays the FQDN (Fully Qualified Domain Name).
</para>
</listitem>
</varlistentry>

<varlistentry>
<term>-i, --ip-address</term>
<listitem>
<para>
displays the IP address(es) of the host.
</para>
</listitem>
</varlistentry>

<varlistentry>
<term>-s, --short</term>
<listitem>
<para>
displays the short host name. This is the host name cut at the first
dot.
</para>
</listitem>
</varlistentry>

<varlistentry>
<term>-v, --verbose</term>
<listitem>
<para>
provide diagnostic information.
</para>
</listitem>
</varlistentry>

<varlistentry>
<term>-y, --yp, --nis</term>
<listitem>
<para>
displays, or, with appropriate privilege, sets the NIS domain name.
</para>
</listitem>
</varlistentry>

</variablelist>
</REFSECT1>
<refsect1>
<title>Future Directions</title>
<para>A future version of this specification may deprecate all the
behavior and options relating to NIS.
<NOTE><title>Rationale</title>
<para>The LSB does not specify NIS, and so commands that alter its
behavior are not required.</para>
</NOTE>
</para>
</refsect1>

<refsect1>
<title>LSB Deprecated Options</title>

<para>The behaviors specified in this section are expected to
disappear from a future version of the LSB; applications should only
use the non-LSB-deprecated behaviors.</para>

<variablelist>

<varlistentry>
<term>-V, --version</term>
<listitem>
<para>
prints version information on standard output and exits successfully.
</para>
</listitem>
</varlistentry>

</variablelist>
</refsect1>

</REFENTRY>
